{"id":14881909,"mediaExerciseId":"cff7d1ac-05cb-41af-b37b-99b5a48f9e1b","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"25","chapterTitle":"Option Valuation","groupId":612507,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":855,"solutions":[{"id":6519579,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are going to determine the effect of the expiration date on the option's value. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"To start with, let us define the **expiration date.**\n\nThis is the period wherein the holder can exercise his right to buy or sell the financial instrument.\n\nIn the time period before the expiration, the option's value will depend either on the rise or decline of stock prices. The movement of the market along with the time determines the value of the option, which, maybe beneficial either on the part of the buyer or seller.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The expiration date has a direct relationship with the option's value. If the option has a longer time to maturity, then the option's value is probably higher. This is because the holder has more time to exercise his rights once the market is in favor of him. \n\nTherefore, the longer the expiry, the higher the option's value. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"cc7c0730-440d-45e4-8985-13b502004916","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nch